<p><em>Fire Elves problems:</em></p>
<p><strong>Fire Elves are likely to have many problems in the future, but most of them haven&rsquo;t actually happened yet, so we&rsquo;ll just pretend they&rsquo;re safe for now</strong></p>
<p><strong>Economic Action</strong>:&nbsp;</p>
<p>Infrastructure (Establishment): Fireport [the Hunger]</p>
<p>Action: Create village &lsquo;Gerdr&rsquo; two squares south of Surt</p>
<p>Even with the ongoing potential Turmoil, Surt needs to expand, and letting unseen threats hem it in is not really an option. Particularly if Surt is to keep up with its neighbors (friendly or not). To that end, the Hunger pushes forward Project Gerdr, an expansion settlement in the newly discovered cove [two squares] to Surt&rsquo;s south. A complete port will have to wait until the settlement itself is established, but for now this should provide a decent base of operations for newcomers heading into Surt&rsquo;s established territory.&nbsp;</p>
<p>After an internal vote within the CPC, the new village is named Gerdr. As with Surt, the name is taken from old Elven mythology (as remembered after years under the Lycans).&nbsp;</p>
<p>In addition, the Expansionary Guard will be sent out to defend the site during and after construction. This should also help provide incoming guests a safe port to dock at on their way to the Potluck.</p>
<p><a href="https://dev71687.service-now.com/nav_to.do?uri=x_339494_mdalpha_rolls.do?sys_id=847b59eedb223300e7a0a08a48961924">Roll</a>: 2 Advantage, 2 Successes</p>
<p><strong>Political Action</strong>:&nbsp;</p>
<p>Spycraft (Cloak and Dagger): Be prepared [Ashwalker Tsun]</p>
<p><em>Includes a Prof die from Cathartic Unity</em></p>
<p>&ldquo;Try to be serious about this, Tsun. It is extremely likely that Surt will be the target of enemy activity this season. For all that you said about &ldquo;stupid bureaucrats&rdquo;, you and I *and the public* know that there was a serious security breach at the filter stations this past winter, and you and I are both aware that Alfyr suffered a similar breach. Someone is setting us up.<br /> &ldquo;I know you have complaints about the Blade Elf presence here, and I&rsquo;ll give you a chance to address them. But that requires there *is* a Surt at the end of this. Keep your troops off the Blade Elves and on the actual policework. Catch something for once.&rdquo;</p>
<p><a href="https://dev71687.service-now.com/nav_to.do?uri=x_339494_mdalpha_rolls.do?sys_id=051f59eedb223300e7a0a08a48961927">Roll</a>, other <a href="https://dev71687.service-now.com/nav_to.do?uri=x_339494_mdalpha_rolls.do?sys_id=3d91f43edb2a3300e7a0a08a489619e6">roll</a>: 1 advantage, 1 success (!)</p>
<p><strong>Military Action:</strong></p>
<p>Conventional Warfare (Defensive Operations): Abundant Force [the Terror]</p>
<p>Conditional action: Deploy detachment Charred Eagles to support Dreamdust anti-Coyote operations</p>
<p>After a long-distance discussion with the Flying Elves, the Dreamdust Elves, and the Blade Elves, the Terror takes the Charred Eagles division southwards, and deploys them in defensive operations in support of the Dreamdust Elves. The Terror&rsquo;s campaign goal is to see the &lsquo;Coyotes&rsquo; at least deterred, with preference for dragging them into at least one engagement; the Coyote strategy appears to be &lsquo;fast raids on soft targets&rsquo;, which suggests that even small losses may deter them from future assaults.</p>
<p>Part one of the Terror&rsquo;s strategy will be to help the Dreamdust elves build more serious defenses in their area (including spike walls, trenches, and other cavalry-counters), and make an effort to study up on known Coyote battle tactics (including talking with the local kobold(?) tribes that live in the area). Part two will be a coordinated effort to detect the next raid before it arrives and force an engagement; this will likely mean setting up a bait convoy, but that&rsquo;s not required if the enemy makes their intentions clear from the start. Part three will be to take captives and try to figure out Coyote situation and grand strategy, and to force capitulance if possible.</p>
<p><a href="https://dev71687.service-now.com/nav_to.do?uri=x_339494_mdalpha_rolls.do?sys_id=b5b9c166db223300e7a0a08a489619aa">Roll</a>: 5 successes</p>
<p><strong>Military Action 2 (motivating with 1 FP):</strong></p>
<p>Conventional Warfare (Defensive Operations): Redundant Force [the Smoke]</p>
<p>Action: deploy the Expansionary Guard to the site of Gerdr</p>
<p><em>Stunt invoked: </em><strong><em>Hot Gates!</em></strong></p>
<p>The likelihood of enemy action at this juncture is dangerously high. Vita, who is effectively the city&rsquo;s top general after the Terror, is ordered to deploy the Expansionary Guard to the site of Gerdr, and prepare to defend it from possible incursion. Aware that the settlement is a precarious position, and the Expansionary Guard is a green unit, the Smoke keeps the civilians prepped for an evacuation, and has the Guard defend the road where possible, with orders to retry to Surt if they are likely to be overwhelmed.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The Smoke decides that some of these operations should take advantage of the cove and the village currently being built -- including village buildings in fortification planning, preparing the road for sapping, etc. The infrastructure damage may hurt Gerdr in the short term, but it&rsquo;ll also make it that much harder for an enemy force to invade.</p>
<p><a href="https://dev71687.service-now.com/nav_to.do?uri=x_339494_mdalpha_rolls.do?sys_id=cc23616edb223300e7a0a08a48961977">Roll</a>: 2 advantage, 2 successes</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Mental Action:</strong></p>
<p>Academics (Research): the Ill Intent [the Fury]</p>
<p>Well, this &ldquo;ritual&rdquo; that Shadimon provided looks promising&hellip; even though, to the Fury, its about straightforward and easy to interpret as a romance novel written in draconic. What&rsquo;s more, it seems somewhat limited -- a random duration, lasting between a single season and a year? Based solely on intent to do harm? There&rsquo;s potential there, but by itself it is somewhat limited, and likely to force the ritual casters to cast it every other season just to keep it from dropping unannounced. So, she decides, why not improve upon it, using this as a basis?</p>
<p>She starts by doing some retargeting. &ldquo;The settlement&rdquo; is a good target, but &ldquo;anyone intending to do harm on the settlement or its occupants&rdquo; is vague and likely to lead to false positives. Narrowing it to &ldquo;individuals obscuring themselves with illusion, transmutation, or polymorph effects, with intent to do harm to two or more individuals, and/or an individual on &lsquo;list of government officials&rdquo; makes for a more complicated search query, but also means the spell only queries magical auras first, and *then* thoughts on the subset, which should reduce the overall energy costs of the spell.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Second, she attempts to extend the ritual by one or more seasons automatically, or at least to a minimum of two seasons and a maximum of four (i.e. 1d3+1).&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://dev71687.service-now.com/nav_to.do?uri=x_339494_mdalpha_rolls.do?sys_id=8b76716edb223300e7a0a08a4896197c">Roll</a>: 2 advantage, 1 success</p>
<p><strong>Character Actions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Smoke action (freebie): </strong>Exploring the Ridge&nbsp;</p>
<p>Survival 22, Know Nature 33</p>
<p><strong>Hunger Action 1</strong>: Checking the filtration system for tampering</p>
<p>Perception 11, Craft (Alchemy) 3`</p>
<p><strong>Hunger Action 2:</strong></p>
<p>Screw the dog&rsquo;s &ldquo;noble intentions&rdquo;. The Hunger knows that it has to know that if they are the same, then were their positions reversed, it would decide that it cannot take the risk that the Hunger would represent. To that end, the Hunger delves into arcane research, attempting to devise an &ldquo;arcane lock&rdquo; variant that will function on a timer. The goal is to create a magically enhanced locking mechanism that even he can&rsquo;t open once its active, and will deactivate after nine hours. If that works, he&rsquo;ll test it on the doorway to the lab -- and add a copy to the cell door once he&rsquo;s certain its solid.</p>
<p>Know (Arcana): 28</p>
<p>He also leaves a few bottles of wine in the cell. If the creature wishes to drink, why not indulge him.</p>
<p><strong>Hunger Action 3:</strong></p>
<p>(A) The transformation has an active casting aura associated with it. (B). The dog insists its mind is the same, but without morality&hellip; which probably indicates it would fall on the &ldquo;evil&rdquo; axis on the philosopher-alchemist Milgram&rsquo;s &ldquo;Moral Alignment Square&rdquo;.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Going off of that, the Hunger wonders if it might be possible to at least &ldquo;alleviate&rdquo; the beast with some sort of &ldquo;alignment inducement&rdquo; -- or that maybe a simple <em>protection from evil</em> potion will ameliorate some of the symptoms. This has enough merit that the Hunger resolves to try that before the next full moon. And if the dog has complaints about this procedure, it should remember that morality and ethics are an important part of blending in with the public. So shut up.</p>
<p>Dispelling is another question&hellip; but is also harder to pull off, as that usually requires direct (and significant) arcane or divine release. However, there are devices that can store this energy, and in fact, there is one in particular that might be well-suited. The Hunger sets to work on modifying a <em>Bead of Newt Prevention</em>, with the goal of tweaking its function so that it would temporarily prevent the curse&rsquo;s transformative effects. Even if this only buys a few minutes, it could literally make the difference between life and death.</p>
<p>Knowledge (Arcana): 28</p>
<p><strong>Barrabus Action 1:</strong></p>
<p>Despite the strong suggestions of *certain people* who seem to think that Barry can find the River Elves&rsquo; secret winter quarters *and* save them in a span of a week, Barry determines that the best use of the remainder of the season is to <em>try and figure out what the hell is going on with the Triumvirate</em>. He understands that there are a lot of external threats going on right now, which is probably taking a lot of their attention, but there&rsquo;s been something very strange going on with those three for the last season, at least. The Hunger keeps being &ldquo;mysteriously absent&rdquo;. The Fury started doing something similar last season (and there&rsquo;s definitely something up with her, but Barry figures a lot of that is just that she&rsquo;s crazy). And now the Terror disappears for a week, only to immediately take the Charred Eagles and head south almost as soon as she got back. What the hell is going on?</p>
<p>Diplomacy (Gather Information): 15</p>
<p>Stealth (to quietly monitor the Hunger and the Fury): 23</p>
<p>Perception (to scan their workplaces for anything unusual): 28</p>
<p>Perform (Comedy) (to distract them and their guards while he&rsquo;s scanning their workplaces for anything unusual): 25</p>
<p><strong>Dogtalk (now on paper!):</strong></p>
