<p>The construction process for Gedr goes smoothly. There is some initial headbutting, with CPC construction teams and the Expansionary Guard arguing about what specific projects take priority versus security, but Smoke is able to keep things running smoothly.</p>
<p>In fact, the biggest problem with the founding of Gedr is that it ends up being <em>more</em> successful than anticipated. A large group of immigrants arrive from the Hilt&rsquo;Inn. They report that they had been staying at the refugee center there until the harsh winter cleared and they were able to travel. Many of them settle in Gedr. Additionally, many merchants who wish to trade with the outside world move large portions of their businesses to Gedr, and finally a large number of people who are just sick of the fractured politics in Surt move as well. Gedr ends up with a larger than anticipated population.</p>
<p>Gedr&rsquo;s population is mostly more sedate and businesslike fire elves, those than want a place to just simply do business in a slightly more stable area than the chaotic swirl of nonsense that is Surt.</p>
<p>The higher population places a toll on your building supplies. Once again, you&rsquo;ve gone a bit over budget. Nothing catastrophic though, you will simply take a <strong>setback die</strong> on any Infrastructure checks next turn.</p>
<p>Gedr is well ready to receive guests by the time of the Potluck, as well. A few basic docks are built, but nothing fancy. It&rsquo;ll work though, especially with the natural shelter of the cove.</p>
<p><strong>Political- </strong>Asking the dark elves for a little help turns out to have been a good idea. Their spyhunters are few in number, but they have skills that the CG and Praesidium don't, namely subtlety. The CG act like traditional guards, and the Praesidium mostly rely on numbers, coverage, and local connections. Neither of them are particularly sneaky, sly types.</p>
<p>This means that the dark elves have a neat little niche to fill. They stay in the background mostly, staying hidden, watching, and listening. They are more than happy to stay out of the spotlight with how chaotic and vibrant Surt is. Turns out, watching from the shadows helps.</p>
<p>Doukas' idea to have CG escorts with the blade elves turns out to be an effective one. The blades complain about their "babysitters," especially at the beginning, but the impromptu guides keep the blade elves from having misunderstandings with the locals. However, this gets dicey in crowded situations. It is on one such occasion during a particularly busy night at the Howl that someone tries to make their move.</p>
<p>Another bar fight distracts the guards. A few insulting words make it to the ears of a group of five blade elf soldiers. Before anyone can account for it, they're ready to take it outside. Right into the waiting arms of a more extremist Praesidium patrol, in a clear alley, with lookouts on the ends</p>
<p>They did not count on the dark elves. A dark elf Spyhunter watching the outside of the Howl recognizes a trap when he sees one. The dark elf can't make it inside because of the crowd, but manages to reach a passing CG patrol in time. The CG makes it to the alley in time, stopping the group before they ambush the blade elves. All are arrested.</p>
<p>The CG and Spyhunters agree that this group was intentionally looking to start an incident that would end up with dead blade elves (or maybe fire elves dead at blade elf hands) and perhaps put a permanent black mark on the two peoples' relationship. Thankfully this has been avoided. The blade elves spend a few days in lockup and receive disciplinary action from Villhook for getting drunk while armed, knowingly getting in a fight, and leaving their mandatory escort behind. A couple of officers in the group are demoted and sent home. The Praesidium members responsible for the plan are taken into Triumvirate custody.</p>
<p>They turn out to be from a tiny extremist sect called the Blue Flame. The group seems to believe that fire elves have even further to go before reaching their true destiny as "perfect flame," whatever the fuck that means. The group measured less than ten, and this represented all their Praesidium members. Considering their leaders fled Surt as soon as the ambush failed, your analysts believe that they may have had outside help.</p>
<p>Thankfully, that's the only major incident with the blade elves. There are a litany of smaller clashes, but far from anything serious. By the end of the season, the majority of non-extremist blade elves are satisfied that the blade elves are genuinely there to help and not to invade.</p>
<p>They're shit at lying anyway.</p>
<h3 id="back">Roleplay Event 2.4.1: <a href="../Bonus/9_A Blade's Edge.php">A Blade's Edge</a></h3>
<p><strong>Military-</strong> The Coyotes are absolutely infuriating to fight, but fight them you do.</p>
<p>The opening weeks of your joint deployment are marked with nigh constant harassing raids, feints, and sabotage. Coyotes come in small groups at random times, harass supply trains, fake charges, and just generally cause trouble. None of these end up being an actual attack, but it gets aggravating.</p>
<p><br />Damage from this is of course limited. The Charred Eagles do a good job of keeping them away from anything actually important. The winged elf rangers also prove absolute masters of their craft as well. Even though they have well more than a hundred miles of territory to cover throughout the season, they do so with extreme prejudice. More often than not, you have warning that a Coyote harassing attack is coming and are able to react and close ranks.</p>
<p>Frustratingly, actually <em>pinning down</em> the Coyotes when they&rsquo;re doing one of these raids proves nearly impossible. Over the course of the raids, you get an idea of just how fast the Coyote elf horses are - with a move speed of about 80 in game terms. Even winged elf scouts can&rsquo;t keep up with that nonsense, and tracking them once they manage to shake visual contact proves nearly impossible. Their habit of using small hills as cover and kicking up small dust storms makes this even worse, allowing them to break contact from even aerial pursuit. People should not be that stealthy on horseback. It should not be legal.</p>
<p>Still, the worst casualty of this phase is the exhaustion. Many of the troops are not used to functioning in this hot of an environment with this aggressive of an operations tempo. It proves taxing on the troops constantly scrambling for raids, and eventually they have had enough. Dust proposes a daring plan and Shadimon and Terror agree, though Shadimon goes to attempt to deliver an ultimatum of some kind to the Coyotes first.</p>
<p>Regardless, a plan like this has a narrow window of opportunity. The fire elves and dreamdust elves cooperate to rig the ambush caravan. The dreamdust elves are a little antsy about setting so many things up to burn, but the fire elves are <em>pumped</em>.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The apparently undefended caravan is sent out. Winged elf rangers spread out to watch for an attack. Dreamdust elves prepare for an ambush and to set the fires. Fire elves prepare for what fire elves do. The Terror is practically vibrating.</p>
<p>The attack comes suddenly, with the Coyotes coming straight at the caravan at full gallop. This attack is not as coordinated as the others, with instead the Coyotes attacking in a massive formation that runs at the head of another massive dust storm. You can see banners with Coyotes embroidered at them flying among the cavalry charge. You may have underestimated them.</p>
<p>They hit the caravan in a ragged formation. Dreamdust elves leap from the wagons, apparently fleeing the attack and leaving the caravan unattended. Coyotes rip open the covers of the wagons to find&hellip; <em>fire.</em> Honestly it&rsquo;s a perfect setup. It could not have gone closer to plan.</p>
<p>The fire elves erupt from the flames. The Terror, in a blur of fire and chain, leaps from the cart and takes charge of the battlefield. With the shock of erupting flames and close combat with anti-cavalry soldiers, the Coyotes are thrown into disarray.</p>
<p>The Terror and her hoplites surround a group of Coyotes - about ten. They call for the Coyotes to dismount and surrender.</p>
<p>One of the Coyotes yells in response: &ldquo;You&rsquo;ll get my head off my shoulders before my ass off my horse, pendeja!&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>The defiant Coyote then whistles and rallies the remaining riders to him. The trapped Coyote riders then proceed to charge the Terror. Not the Elect surrounding her, not in a breakout. They charge <em>her personally</em>. All ten of them.</p>
<p>Terror, with the help of her Elect, is able to survive the attack and still be standing. Most of the trapped Coyotes are killed. Two escape on horseback. Three horses are captured, along with the Coyote who yelled to start the attack. Terror appears to have gone out of her way to leave that guy alive, and he disappears into fire elf custody.</p>
<p>The remaining Coyotes retreat from the attack in disarray. They do organize and pull their usual disappearing act, but the winged elves notice something off. There are significantly fewer Coyotes than they thought. They appear to be riding in a loose formation, specifically intended to make it look like there are more of them than there actually are.</p>
<p>After conferring with the assembled military leaders, the cause is clear. This is a distraction. The Coyotes want you to think that they have a full division active in this region, when clearly they do not. If the division that attacked the nomads isn&rsquo;t here though, where are they?</p>
<p>Oh. Oh no.</p>
<p><em>To: All; From: Baijani: Asavardi under attack by Coyote elves. Casualties, hostages, looting in progress. No assistance expected now, but revenge would be lovely. Fuckem.</em></p>
<p>Baijani is right. There&rsquo;s no way you could reach Asavardi in time.</p>
<p>Worse news comes back. The scout that travelled with Shadimon returns, alone and injured. By apparently sheer horrifically bad luck, Shadimon was shot down. The scout last saw Shadimon getting a net thrown over him and dragged to the ground by Coyote riders at Coldwater. He has been captured.</p>
<p><em>Though they did serious damage to the attacking Coyotes, your Division was under significant stress keeping up with the Coyotes constant raids. They have the Fatigued condition until the end of Summer. The Ashkin who were already fatigued are Exhausted.</em></p>
<p><em>Notably you have the defiant Coyote captive. However, getting brained by Terror&rsquo;s hammer has left him worse for wear. Even after magic healing, he is down unconscious with a fever. Healers tell you that forcing him to regain consciousness might permanently damage his mind or kill him. What you do with him is up to you.</em></p>
<p><strong>Mental- </strong>As it turns out, the winged elves are <em>extremely</em> good at detail oriented magic, and this is not exactly the Fury&rsquo;s forte. At first glance of the pages describing the ritual, she assumes this will not be a big deal. The raw magical power needed to fuel this ritual is not particularly great, nor is there anything particularly catastrophic that could go wrong. The devils, however, hide in the details.</p>
<p>The Fury assumes she will be able to knock back this ritual no problem. After reading the overall description of the ritual, she believes it will be easy enough to research and begins to add her own little improvements to the ritual itself. As it turns out, this was a mistake.</p>
<p>While it may not be a particularly powerful ritual, it <em>is</em> a particularly complicated one. This spell involves multiple different types of divination magic, as well as abjuration. Each of these different types of magic weave together, relying on each other to make the ritual function. These factors combine to make this ritual actually rather difficult to adapt to her particular casting style.</p>
<p>If she had simply been trying to copy it and started that way, she may have succeeded. However her self confident belief in her abilities led her to add many difficult and complicated additions to the spell. She loses too much time trying to implement these improvements with the original ritual, and ends up simply running out of time without a viable version of the ritual ready.</p>
<p><strong>Characters-</strong></p>
<p><strong>Smoke- </strong>The site has been here for some time. Most of the tracks are old and worn down. The ridge and the cave in particular, however, are sheltered and not worn nearly as much. She isn&rsquo;t able to get as much as she really wanted, but she&rsquo;s able to get some solid information.</p>
<p>The most conclusive thing she&rsquo;s able to figure out is that there was only one individual in the cave. There are boot and pawprints, but they were both from the same individual. There&rsquo;s one print where someone was clearly in mid-shapeshift. Further, with her knowledge of tracking, she&rsquo;s reasonably certain that this was a large female wolf.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The wolf was badly injured when she entered the cave. Smoke <em>thinks</em> the wolf may have been coming <em>from</em> the direction of Surt, not towards it. The wolf was limping with what was definitely a broken leg, and probably numerous other injuries. She stopped, laid down, and bled from numerous injuries for a bit. She shifted into humanoid form, then back into wolf. The wolf tracks leaving the cave are not injured, so Smoke suspects the wolf may have used some kind of magic healing as a humanoid then shifted back to wolf.</p>
<p>The wolf then left the cave and headed towards the overlook that the Terror stayed at. It&rsquo;s kind of hard to make out any kind of tracks on the rock, so after that it&rsquo;s not clear. It&rsquo;s hard to tell because of the imprint of Terror&rsquo;s fat b- I mean large, well armored frame sat down next to the rock, but Smoke thinks the wolf <em>may</em> have laid down there for some time, watching Surt. That is about when the symbol was carved. The carving was done with the toe claw from a paw, not any kind of tool. After that, Smoke&rsquo;s not sure. The wolf got up to leave, but she can&rsquo;t make out any specific direction due to the age of the tracks.</p>
<p>Smoke has her theories, but Terror is free to decide what she thinks all of this means.</p>
<p><strong>Hunger- Filters- </strong>The Hunger&rsquo;s initial inspection reveals nothing out of place. The Hunger, however, is not one to take anything on a simple spot check. While there has been no obvious gratuitous sabotage, at least one of the groups spying on his allies has demonstrated a strong knowledge of alchemy. There is a high chance of such tampering.</p>
<p>Hunger takes randomized samples from every filter, as well as a variety of water samples. He goes over them with a fine tooth comb. Literally, actually. He still has plenty of his original notes and a large amount of original samples of the mixtures used to create the filters originally. He does a series of blind tests, examining the samples for even extremely subtle signs of tampering.</p>
<p>Interestingly enough, he finds nothing. None of the samples he takes indicate tampering. He repeats the test a few more time with more random samples, and gets the same results. Finally, he fully examines each individual potential failure point in the purification center both with magic and by hand.</p>
<p>No tampering. In the end, the project takes him nearly as long as researching it did in the first damned place, but he&rsquo;s certain whatever happened the purification process was not tampered with and the water it produces is still exactly what they need.</p>
<p><strong>Arcane Lock/Bead- </strong>First of all, the research on Protection from Evil hits an immediate brick wall. Protection from Evil only protects your mind from outside evil influences. The dog is well and truly part of him by this point. It won&rsquo;t do any good.</p>
<p>Research on Arcane Lock and an Anti-Polymorph bead turns out fairly easy. First of all, a custom version of Arcane Lock would be easy enough to make. It actually might be slightly easier to tweak the spell to have a fixed duration. Not too much of a hassle, especially if it&rsquo;s put on an item. Only has to work once per day.</p>
<p>The bead is a bit trickier. Activation is the problem, mostly. It could be tricked to delay a transformation, of course, much like that first transformation. Might give him a chance to reach safety. The dog, of course, has no desire to activate such an item. Maybe it could be worked into a trap of some kind? That, and he still has no idea if he would regain control of himself if the transformation is reversed, or if so for how long.</p>
<p>Then, he runs into a serious problem. He is not an arcane caster, nor magic item crafter. Neither of those base spells are available as extracts. He would have to get help to make these, and it would be <em>mighty</em> suspicious.&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Barrabus- </strong>Ever the snoop and busybody, Barrabus gets to work. He chats up a few government workers to see if they know anything, but quickly gets nowhere. Just more rumors that can&rsquo;t be confirmed. He does, however, gather a few things that are useful, not the least of which is where Hunger&rsquo;s lab is.</p>
<p>Barrabus is able to sweet talk his way into the central government compound enough, but getting into Hunger&rsquo;s office turns out to be quite the challenge. He manages to slip in past a cleaning staff, but can&rsquo;t find the entrance to Hunger&rsquo;s lab. Curious, he manages to snoop around Hunger&rsquo;s desk but finds little useful, other than some odd orders for paralysis flowers.</p>
<p>Hunger enters the room while Barrabus is snooping, but he is able to duck behind Hunger&rsquo;s desk before he&rsquo;s spotted. Hunger does something with a bookcase to enter his lab. Barrabus isn&rsquo;t able to spot it on account of hiding, but notes just how secure Hunger&rsquo;s door is - and just how many locks he secures on the way in. Barrabus notes that he&rsquo;ll make another attempt to snoop in the Hunger&rsquo;s lab some other time. It sounds like a lot of work to get in there.</p>
<p>Fury&rsquo;s research are turns out to be much less secure. Scorch marks on the floor, for some reason. Not that odd, I guess. He fiddles around her office for a bit. He&rsquo;s got some training in spellcraft, enough to recognize rituals. He has a pretty good idea what most are, until he notices a hidden batch of files at the bottom of a drawer in her armoire.</p>
<p>These contain rituals he doesn&rsquo;t recognize. Powerful looking ones. Old looking ones. Jackpot! He digs through these pages and pages of grim looking rituals, but can&rsquo;t put together much other than the fact that they look very dark and very dangerous. While he is snooping, he is interrupted&hellip;</p>
<p>Fury is standing at the door, arms folded, sparking. Staring right at him. With his hands still in her drawer full of drawers.</p>
<p>Oops.</p>
<p><br /><strong>Congratulations! </strong>You have survived another year in this strange and chaotic land! As a reward for your perseverance, you receive one skill point to distribute as you wish!</p>
